President Trump visited the Border Patrol National Targeting Center in Sterling, Virginia, where he was briefed on the challenges faced by law enforcement in securing the border and combating illegal immigration. Secretary of Homeland Security Kirstjen Nielsen and other officials highlighted the need for border security measures, closing legal loopholes, and cracking down on drug trafficking and gang violence, particularly by MS-13. The officials also emphasized the importance of cooperation from other countries in taking back their citizens who have been deported from the United States. President Trump expressed his support for strong border security and tough enforcement measures to protect American citizens. He called on Congress to pass legislation to address these issues and criticized Democrats for not being willing to make a deal on immigration.